2A 101st Legislative Session 2
2026 South Dakota Legislature
Senate Bill 2
AMENDM ENT 2A
FOR THE INTRODUCED BILL
Introduced by: Senator Crabtree
1 An Act to provide that a firearm silencer is not a controlled weapon.
2 BE IT ENACTED BY THE LEGISLATURE OF THE STATE OF SOUTH DAKOTA:
3 Section 1. That § 22-1-2 be AMENDED:
4 22-1-2. Terms used in this title mean:
5 (1) If applied to the intent with which an act is done or omitted:
6 (a) The words, "malice, maliciously," and all derivatives thereof import a wish to
7 intentionally vex, annoy, or injure another person, established either by
8 proof or presumption of law;
9 (b) The words, "intent, intentionally," and all derivatives thereof, import a
10 specific design to cause a certain result or, if the material part of a charge
11 is the violation of a prohibition against conduct of a certain nature,
12 regardless of what the offender intends to accomplish thereby, a specific
13 design to engage in conduct of that nature;
14 (c) The words, "knowledge, knowingly," and all derivatives thereof, import only
15 a knowledge that the facts exist which bring the act or omission within the
16 provisions of any statute. A person has knowledge if that person is aware
17 that the facts exist which bring the act or omission within the provisions of
18 any statute. Knowledge of the unlawfulness of such act or omission is not
19 required;
20 (d) The words, "reckless, recklessly," and all derivatives thereof, import a
21 conscious and unjustifiable disregard of a substantial risk that the offender's
22 conduct may cause a certain result or may be of a certain nature. A person
23 is reckless with respect to circumstances if that person consciously and
24 unjustifiably disregards a substantial risk that such circumstances may
25 exist;
Underscores indicate new language.
Overstrikes indicate deleted language.

2A 2 2
1 (e) The words, "neglect, negligently," and all words derived thereof, import a
2 want of attention to the nature or probable consequences of an act or
3 omission which a prudent person ordinarily bestows in acting in his or her
4 own concerns;
5 (f) If the section defining an offense provides that negligence suffices to establish
6 an element thereof, then recklessness, knowledge, intent, or malice also
7 constitutes sufficient culpability for such element. If recklessness suffices to
8 establish an element of the offense, then knowledge, intent or malice also
9 constitutes sufficient culpability for such element. If knowledge suffices to
10 establish an element of an offense, then intent or malice also constitutes
11 sufficient culpability for such element. If intent suffices to establish an
12 element of an offense, then malice also constitutes sufficient culpability for
13 such element;
14 (2) "Actor," the person who takes the active part in a transaction;
15 (3) "Affirmative defense," an issue involving an alleged defense to which, unless the
16 state's evidence raises the issue, the defendant, to raise the issue, must present
17 some credible evidence. If the issue involved in an affirmative defense is raised,
18 then the guilt of the defendant must be established beyond a reasonable doubt as
19 to that issue as well as all other elements of the offense;
20 (4) "Antique firearm," any firearm, including any firearm with a matchlock, flintlock,
21 percussion cap or similar type of ignition system, manufactured before 1899, and
22 any replica of any firearm described in this section if such replica is not designed
23 or redesigned for using rimfire or conventional centerfire fixed ammunition or if it
24 uses rimfire or conventional centerfire fixed ammunition which is no longer
25 manufactured in the United States and which is not readily available in the ordinary
26 channels of commercial trade;
27 (5) "Check," any check, draft, order or other commercial device which orders a financial
28 institution to pay a sum certain of money on its presentment;
29 (6) "Concealed," any firearm that is totally hidden from view. If any part of the firearm
30 is capable of being seen, it is not concealed;
31 (7) "Consideration," any type of property or thing of legal value, whether delivered in
32 the past, or present, or to be delivered in the future. The term includes an
33 unfulfilled promise to deliver. The term may include an advantage or benefit to the
34 promisor or a loss or detriment to the promisee. Any amount, advantage or
35 inconvenience, no matter how trifling, is sufficient to constitute consideration;
Underscores indicate new language.
Overstrikes indicate deleted language.

2A 3 2
1 (8) "Controlled weapon" includes any firearm silencer, a machine gun, or and short
2 shotgun, as those terms are defined in subdivisions (17), (23), and (46) of this
3 section, but does not include a firearm silencer;
4 (9) "Crime of violence," any of the following crimes or an attempt to commit, or a
5 conspiracy to commit, or a solicitation to commit any of the following crimes:
6 murder, manslaughter, rape, aggravated assault, riot, robbery, burglary in the first
7 degree, arson, kidnapping, felony sexual contact as defined in § 22-22-7, felony
8 child abuse as defined in § 26-10-1, or any other felony in the commission of which
9 the perpetrator used force, or was armed with a dangerous weapon, or used any
10 explosive or destructive device;
11 (9A) "Critical infrastructure facility," any of the following facilities, whether in operation,
12 idle, or under construction, maintenance, or repair, that which are enclosed by a
13 fence or other physical barrier that is obviously designed to exclude trespassers
14 and are clearly marked with a sign that is posted on the property and reasonably
15 likely to come to the attention of any trespasser that, and which indicates that
16 entry is forbidden, or any pole or tower used for any of the purposes in this
17 subdivision, whether enclosed or marked with a sign or not:
18 (a) Electric utility facility, including a power generation facility, an electric
19 transmission facility, an electric station or substation, or any other facility
20 used to support the generation, transmission, or distribution of electricity;
21 (b) Water tower, municipal or rural water system well, water intake structure,
22 or water treatment facility;
23 (c) Natural gas utility facility, including a regulator station, a compressor
24 station, an odorization facility, a mainline valve, a natural gas storage
25 facility, or any other facility used to support the acquisition, transmission,
26 distribution, or storage of natural gas;
27 (d) Tank farm, pipeline terminal, pipeline, pump or compressor station or
28 storage facility for gasoline, crude or refined or synthetic oil, ethanol,
29 propane, liquid natural gas, or other hazardous liquid;
30 (e) Transportation facility, including a port, railroad switching yard, or trucking
31 terminal;
32 (f) Hazardous waste storage, treatment, or disposal facility;
33 (g) Oil and gas locations, facilities, and equipment, including temporary drilling
34 rigs, permanent oil and gas product facilities, and artificial lift equipment;
Underscores indicate new language.
Overstrikes indicate deleted language.

2A 4 2
1 (h) Communications services facility, infrastructure or equipment involved in
2 the carriage of essential communications services for both wired and
3 wireless communications, switching, routing, repeater/amplifier equipment
4 or other electronic equipment, macro and micro wireless towers using
5 federally licensed spectrum, video headend equipment, and satellite
6 communications receiver or transmission equipment;
7 (i) Dam that is owned by the state or a subdivision;
8 (j) Facility either(i) whose owner or operator is required to submit a risk
9 management plan under the federal Chemical Safety Information, Site
10 Security, and Fuels Regulatory Relief Act (, 42 U.S.C. § 7412(r) (January 1,
11 20252026); or (ii) is identified and regulated by the United States
12 Department of Homeland Security Chemical Facility Anti–Terrorism
13 Standards (CFATS) program; or
14 (k) Any construction area, pipe yard, or laydown yard for any of the above,
15 whether permanent or temporary in nature;
16 (10) "Dangerous weapon" or "deadly weapon," any firearm, stun gun, knife, or device,
17 instrument, material, or substance, whether animate or inanimate, which is
18 calculated or designed to inflict death or serious bodily harm, or by the manner in
19 which it is used is likely to inflict death or serious bodily harm;
20 (11) "Dealer in stolen property," any person who:
21 (a) Is found in possession or control of property stolen from two or more persons
22 on separate occasions; or
23 (b) Has received stolen property in another transaction within the year preceding
24 the commencement of the prosecution; or
25 (c) Trades in property similar to the type of stolen property received and acquires
26 such property for a consideration which that person knows is substantially
27 below its reasonable value;
28 (12) "Deprive," to take or to withhold property of another or to dispose of property of
29 another so as to make it unlikely that the owner will receive it;
30 (13) "Destructive device,"
31 (a) Any bomb, grenade, explosive missile, or similar device or any launching
32 device therefor; or
33 (b) Any breakable container which contains a flammable liquid with a flashpoint
34 of one hundred and fifty degrees Fahrenheit or less and has a wick or similar
35 device capable of being ignited;
Underscores indicate new language.
Overstrikes indicate deleted language.

2A 5 2
1 (c) The term does not include "permissible fireworks," defined by § 34-37-5; any
2 device which is neither designed nor redesigned for use as a weapon; any
3 device, although originally designed for use as a weapon, which is
4 redesigned for use as a signaling, pyrotechnic, line throwing, safety or
5 similar device; surplus ordnance sold, loaned or given by the secretary of
6 the army pursuant to the provisions of 10 U.S.C. §§ 4684(2), 4685, or 4686
7 (January 1, 2026); or any other device which that is an antique or is a rifle
8 which that the owner intends to use solely for sporting purposes;
9 (14) "Explosive," any substance, or combination of substances, that is used for the
10 purpose of detonation and which, upon exposure to any external or internal force
11 or condition, is capable of a relatively instantaneous release of gas and heat. The
12 term does not include "permissible fireworks," as defined by in § 34-37-5;
13 (15) "Financial institution," a bank, insurance company, credit union, savings and loan
14 association, investment trust, or other organization held out to the public as a place
15 of deposit of funds or medium of savings or collective investment;
16 (16) "Firearm," any weapon from which a projectile or projectiles may be discharged by
17 gunpowder. As used in this subdivision, the term, "gunpowder," includes any
18 propellant that upon oxidization emits heat and light and is commonly used in
19 firearms cartridges;
20 (17) "Firearm silencer," any instrument, attachment, weapon, or appliance for causing
21 the firing of any gun, revolver, pistol, or other firearm to be silent, or intended to
22 lessen or muffle the noise of the firing of any such weapon;
23 (18) "Government," the United States, any state, county, municipality, school district,
24 or other political unit, or any department, agency, or subdivision of any of the
25 foregoing, or any corporation or other association carrying out the functions of any
26 of the foregoing;
27 (19) "Immediate family," any spouse, child, parent, or guardian of the victim;
28 (20) "Insanity," the condition of a person temporarily or partially deprived of reason,
29 upon proof that at the time of committing the act, the person was incapable of
30 knowing its wrongfulness, but not including an abnormality manifested only by
31 repeated unlawful or antisocial behavior;
32 (21) "Intoxication," a disturbance of mental or physical capacities resulting from the
33 introduction of substances into the body. Intoxication is not, in itself, a mental
34 disease or defect;
Underscores indicate new language.
Overstrikes indicate deleted language.

2A 6 2
1 (22) "Law enforcement officer," any officer, prosecutor, or employee of the state or any
2 of its political subdivisions or of the United States, or, while on duty, an agent or
3 employee of a railroad or express company, or security personnel of an airline or
4 airport, who is responsible for the prevention, detection, or prosecution of crimes,
5 for the enforcement of the criminal or highway traffic laws of the state, or for the
6 supervision of confined persons or those persons on supervised release or
7 probation;
8 (22A) "Loaded firearm," any functional firearm that contains a cartridge, shell, or
9 projectile in the chamber, including any chamber in the cylinder of a revolver;
10 (23) "Machine gun," any firearm, whatever its size and usual designation, that
11 automatically discharges two or more cartridges by a single function of the firing
12 device;
13 (24) "Mental illness," any substantial psychiatric disorder of thought, mood or behavior,
14 which affects a person at the time of the commission of the offense, and which
15 impairs a person's judgment, but not to the extent that the person is incapable of
16 knowing the wrongfulness of such act. Mental illness does not include abnormalities
17 manifested only by repeated criminal or otherwise antisocial conduct;
18 (25) "Moral turpitude," an act done contrary to justice, honesty, principle, or good
19 morals, as well as an act of baseness, vileness, or depravity in the private and
20 social duties which a person owes to his fellow man or to society in general;
21 (26) "Motor vehicle," any automobile, motor truck, motorcycle, house trailer, trailer
22 coach, cabin trailer, or any vehicle propelled by power other than muscular power;
23 (27) "Obtain,"
24 (a) In relation to property, to bring about a transfer or purported transfer of a
25 legal interest in the property, whether to the actor or another; or
26 (b) In relation to labor or service, to secure performance thereof;
27 (28) "Occupied structure," any structure:
28 (a) Which is the permanent or temporary habitation of any person, whether or
29 not any person is actually present;
30 (b) Which at the time is specially adapted for the overnight accommodation of
31 any person, whether or not any person is actually present; or
32 (c) In which at the time any person is present;
33 (29) "Offense" or "public offense," any crime, petty offense, violation of a city or county
34 ordinance, or act prohibited by state or federal law;
